A Scottish study found that statins reduce heart disease risk for men with short telomeres.
Telomere length could help identify those at risk and guide statin treatment.
A gene variant increases heart disease risk in women.
Gum disease may lead to pancreatic cancer.
Echocardiography is a reliable predictor of heart disease severity.
Stress in childhood can impact heart disease risk.
Air pollution increases cardiovascular disease risk in postmenopausal women.
Reducing pollution could lower disease rates.
Overall, genetics, lifestyle, and environmental factors play significant roles in heart disease development.
